{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s10_4",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b78dc3",
"children":[
"Most patients with thyrotoxicosis benefit from β-blockers to reduce adrenergic symptoms rapidly. Available treatment strategies for hyperthyroidism include antithyroid drugs, radioactive iodine therapy (",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sup",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"131"
]
},
"I), and thyroid surgery."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0aedf7",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Radioactive iodine"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"f9346f",
"children":[
"toxic multinodular goiter"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"0ccc8e",
"children":[
"toxic adenoma"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"6e9bca",
"children":[
"Graves disease (usually following failed drug therapy)"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"aa13e0",
"children":[
"Radioactive iodine is not used during pregnancy or breastfeeding and may aggravate Graves ophthalmopathy."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"223524",
"children":[
"Moderate to severe Graves ophthalmopathy may require treatment with glucocorticoids, surgery, or teprotumumab."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"9dd962",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Antithyroid drugs"
]
},
" may lead to a drug-free remission of Graves disease in up to 50% of patients after 2 years of treatment."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"3",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_en_s10_inline_t3"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"ae8c01",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Thyroidectomy"
]
},
" is preferred as definitive therapy for hyperthyroidism:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"c0acf3",
"children":[
"large goiter with compressive symptoms"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"b0cec7",
"children":[
"intolerance to other therapies"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"773787",
"children":[
"Subclinical hyperthyroidism is diagnosed by TSH suppression with normal T",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"4"
]
},
" and T",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"3"
]
},
" levels. Treatment is recommended for TSH <0.1 μU/L and patients with symptoms."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"4",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_en_s10_inline_t4"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"1368f7",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"A fever or sore throat in a patient taking methimazole or propylthiouracil should be presumed to be agranulocytosis until proven otherwise."
]
},
" "
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s10_5",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"74eed0",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"An asymptomatic 78-year-old woman has a serum TSH level of 0.2 μU/mL. Serum T",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"3"
]
},
" and T",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"4"
]
},
" levels are normal."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"8bf2f9",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose subclinical hyperthyroidism. For management, choose to repeat thyroid tests in 4 to 6 months."
]
}
]
}
]
},
